Hour9 Regular Expressions

Wildcards(pattern)     --a way of specifying several files in an easy way.

Table 9.2 Regular Expression Symbols

Symbol	  Meaning
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
          Repeaters
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
*         Repeats the previous regular expression any number of times(including zero times).
+	  Repeats the previous regular expression any number of times(at least one time).
?         The previous regular expression matches zero or one time
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
          Grouping/Character Groups
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\(...\)   Groups the text for later reference or to overcome precedence problem.
[...]	  Matches any of the characters within the group.(But only one character, if you need to
	  match a number, combine this with *,+,or ?.)
[^...]	  Matches any character not in this group
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
          Positions
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
^         Matches the beginning of the line or string.
$	  Matches the end of line or string.
\<	  Matches the beginning of a word.
\>	  Matches the end of a word.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
          Special Characters
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
.         Matches any character.
\w        Matches any character from a word(in most case, equal to [0-9 a-z A-A]).
\W	  Matches any character not from a word([^0-9 a-z A-Z]).

3. Special characters in regular expression: $, ^, ., *, +, [, ], \.

4. Repeating Elements: Regular expressions are built using a number of special characters that add special meaning to the string.

5. combining Regular Expressions: A and B == AB
   	     	     		  A or  B == A \| B

6.A general rule of thumb that you can use is that *, +, and ? need their arguments enclosed in parentheses unless the argument is a single letter.(The preceding problem)

7. Character Groups is a way of defining a group of possible characters.
   character groups can be negated.